Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# import libraries for data manipulation
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# import libraries for data visualization
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
tab10 = plt.get_cmap('tab10')
sns.set_palette(tab10.colors)
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(8, 3), bins="auto"):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (10, 8))
    bins: number of bins (default "auto")
    """
    f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=1, # Number of rows of the subplot grid
        ncols=2, # Number of columns of the subplot grid
        sharex=True,  # The X-axis will be shared among all the subplots
        gridspec_kw={"width_ratios": (.25, .75)},
        figsize=figsize
    )

    # Creating the subplots
    # Boxplot will be created and the mean value of the column will be indicated using some symbol
    sns.boxplot(x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color='lightcoral')

    # For histogram
    sns.histplot(x=feature, kde=True, ax=ax_hist, bins=bins)
    ax_hist.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='skyblue', linestyle='--')      # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

    plt.show()

#Analysing average ratings and order costs of Restaurants with order count more than 5
restaurant_with_more_orders = df_copy.groupby(['restaurant_name', 'rating'])['order_id'].count().reset_index(name='order_count')

# Filter restaurants with at least 5 orders
filtered_restaurants = restaurant_with_more_orders.groupby('restaurant_name')['order_count'].sum().reset_index()
filtered_restaurants_list = filtered_restaurants[filtered_restaurants['order_count'] > 5]['restaurant_name'].tolist()
restaurant_ratings = restaurant_with_more_orders[restaurant_with_more_orders['restaurant_name'].isin(filtered_restaurants_list)]
restaurant_ratings = restaurant_ratings.groupby(['restaurant_name']).agg({'rating': 'mean','order_count':'sum'}).reset_index()

fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 6))
# Bar plot for order count (primary y-axis)
sns.barplot(x='restaurant_name', y='order_count', data=restaurant_ratings, ax=ax1, color='skyblue')
ax1.set_xlabel('Restaurant Name')
ax1.set_ylabel('Order Count', color='skyblue')
plt.xticks(rotation=90,)

# Create secondary y-axis for average rating
ax2 = ax1.twinx()

# Line plot for average rating (secondary y-axis)
sns.lineplot(x='restaurant_name', y='rating', data=restaurant_ratings, ax=ax2, color='coral', marker='o')
ax2.set_ylabel('Average Rating', color='coral')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='coral')

plt.title('Restaurant Performance: Order Count and Average Rating')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  1. None of the above restaurants have extremely low ratings.Average ratings are above 4.
  2. The restaurants like Shake Shack' with average rating above 4.4 and high order count indicate good establishment with high demand and positive ratings
  3. The restaurants like 'Otto Enoteca Pizzeria' with high average rating but lower order count indicate a need of better offers/pricing /visibility to their clients
  4. Restaurants like 'blue ribbon Fried Chicken' with high order count but lower rating (relatively to other restaurants) indicate a need to improve their quality/services to maintain customer satisfaction

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [ ]:
def revenue(x):
    if x > 20:
        return x*0.25
    elif x > 5 and x<= 20:
        return x*0.15
    else:
        return 0

df_copy['Revenue'] = df_copy['cost_of_the_order'].apply(revenue)
total_net_revenue = df_copy['Revenue'].sum()
print("The total revenue of the company is:" ,round(total_net_revenue))

The total revenue of the company is: 6166

Recommendations:¶

  1. For better customer experience,it is best to have a recommendation system that projects best rated and best selling food items to clients.

One way to achieve this is to get more customer ratings and feedback.

  1. Foodhub must start some promotions that benefit the customers who rate more. More than 60% of the customers have not rated the services which makes it difficult to analyze the issues.

  2. 784 customers have placed only single order. One potential reason why customers stopped ordering can be lack of expected services but because reviews are very less, it is difficult to confirm this. More feedback can help here.

Also, offers for repeated ordering can encourage customers to order repeatedly.

  1. Foodhub needs to find out cause of high delivery times specially during weekdays and they need to reduce it. Lower delivery times increase number of ratings too.

  2. FoodHub must work with new or low performing resturants to introduce more meals at price range where customers are more attracted. Offering that price range can attract more customers to these restaurants.

  3. Foodhub can provide offers to high demand restaurants (which have more orders) as they serve most of the orders.

  4. Very less cuisines have high order count. Foodhub should offer discounts to attract customers to the other cuisines to increase their demand.
